00:00:19,660 --> 00:00:19,788
Scott: Pund.

5
00:00:21,281 --> 00:00:22,044
Rym: I say it, Pund.

6
00:00:22,325 --> 00:00:24,573
Rym: I see you people in the forum seem to disagree on that.

7
00:00:24,814 --> 00:00:28,940
Rym: I have a feeling that the word evolved separately in many different areas.

8
00:00:29,760 --> 00:00:31,909
Scott: Yeah, that seems to be the logic.

9
00:00:31,969 --> 00:00:34,740
Scott: I mean, you know, one guy sees- that's what happens to the internet!

10
00:00:35,162 --> 00:00:42,796
Scott: One guy does something, it spreads to internet-enabled people in different areas, and then it spreads from those internet-enabled people to their circle of friends.

11
00:00:42,817 --> 00:00:43,339
Scott: You know, like a web!

12
00:00:43,880 --> 00:00:44,220
Scott: A web.

13
00:00:46,843 --> 00:00:52,405
Rym: Because I actually remember when we were at RIT and we always said Pund, like everyone did, and then the freshmen.

14
00:00:52,445 --> 00:00:53,450
Rym: We call them the freshmen.

15
00:00:53,510 --> 00:00:57,145
Rym: They're actually almost graduated by now, but we still call them the freshmen.

16
00:00:57,727 --> 00:01:00,940
Rym: But when they got to RIT, they said Pund, which just sounded weird.

17
00:01:01,461 --> 00:01:06,415
Scott: Well, because on the internet, before now, when we have Skype, most people did things by text.

18
00:01:06,676 --> 00:01:15,760
Scott: So, one guy types P-W-N-3-D or something, and everyone in that game has a different pronunciation in their mind, and then who knows what it really is.

19
00:01:16,400 --> 00:01:23,440
Scott: So when nerds actually start getting together physically and talking, and one guy says Pund, another guy says Pund, another guy says Pund.

20
00:01:23,520 --> 00:01:23,875
Rym: Hoedown!

21
00:01:24,343 --> 00:01:24,660
Scott: Hootenanny.

22
00:01:24,720 --> 00:01:25,379
Scott: Hoedown Hootenanny!

23
00:01:25,580 --> 00:01:27,160
Scott: Hoedown Hootenanny Hootenanny Hootenanny Hootenanny Hootenanny.

24
00:01:27,260 --> 00:01:32,780
Rym: Yeah, but anyway, it's video game day, and we've got two video game day newses.

25
00:01:33,700 --> 00:01:39,239
Rym: So, World of Warcraft, you all know that I'd rather dislike it, but-- Yeah, we can't stop talking about it.

26
00:01:39,400 --> 00:01:43,160
Rym: Because it always makes news, and once again, it's made news.

27
00:01:43,980 --> 00:01:49,680
Rym: Now, there's this guy, and he made some sort of unofficial strategy guide to World of Warcraft.

28
00:01:50,120 --> 00:01:50,727
Scott: Strategy.

29
00:01:51,112 --> 00:01:51,760
Scott: Play a lot.

30
00:01:52,261 --> 00:01:55,940
Rym: Well, like, he gave advice on where to level and how to level and various things about the game.

31
00:01:55,940 --> 00:01:59,220
Scott: Places where other people aren't, and the monsters aren't going to kill you.

32
00:01:59,380 --> 00:02:04,660
Rym: Now, instead of publishing this as a book, he published it as a book on eBay.

33
00:02:05,141 --> 00:02:05,639
Rym: No big deal.

34
00:02:06,441 --> 00:02:09,070
Rym: And you think, "Alright, you sell him, I think, $15 a pop.

35
00:02:09,110 --> 00:02:10,013
Rym: I think that's a cool thing.

36
00:02:10,073 --> 00:02:11,699
Rym: I think he's a nice entrepreneurial-type

37
00:02:11,719 --> 00:02:11,960
Rym: person.".

38
00:02:12,080 --> 00:02:12,522
Scott: Yeah, I know.

39
00:02:12,582 --> 00:02:18,099
Scott: Most people go to just-- they write a one in text, they put it on GameFAQs, you know, "This guy made a real book, so

40
00:02:18,120 --> 00:02:18,180
Scott: hey.".

41
00:02:18,300 --> 00:02:23,060
Rym: And I point out that he didn't steal anything, he didn't even use any intellectual property.

42
00:02:23,060 --> 00:02:27,840
Rym: I mean, he didn't reveal storylines, he only used a few screenshots that are clearly fair use.

43
00:02:28,140 --> 00:02:40,120
Rym: And he has a huge disclaimer in the front of the book and the back explaining that he has not affiliated in any way with World of Warcraft or any of the companies involved, and that the guide is entirely unofficial and unacknowledged.

44
00:02:40,621 --> 00:02:40,953
Scott: Mm-hmm.

45
00:02:41,320 --> 00:02:43,808
Rym: Despite this, Blizzard, the Vendee et

46
00:02:43,968 --> 00:02:44,109
Rym: al.,

47
00:02:44,430 --> 00:02:52,380
Rym: have proceeded to send takedown notices to him and to eBay, to threaten to file suit under all sorts of things like the DMCA, and trademark infringement.

48
00:02:52,960 --> 00:02:53,282
Scott: Wow.

49
00:02:53,423 --> 00:02:54,629
Scott: Alright, so, well, okay.

50
00:02:54,910 --> 00:02:56,860
Scott: Trademark infringement, I can understand, see.

51
00:02:57,380 --> 00:03:01,160
Scott: 'Cause let's say I wanted to write a book about the history of some football team, right?

52
00:03:01,602 --> 00:03:02,300
Rym: You don't need permission.

53
00:03:02,660 --> 00:03:09,540
Scott: I don't, but however, if I use, like, the logos of the football team, or if I use any statistics, they can get you.

54
00:03:10,220 --> 00:03:16,520
Rym: Well, statistics, no, because statistics, as long as they are gathered, are a fact, and facts cannot be held by IP laws like that.

55
00:03:16,941 --> 00:03:22,139
Scott: Uh, they're actually, all the sports statistics are held by these companies, or these two companies, or something like that.

56
00:03:22,199 --> 00:03:22,520
Scott: It's weird.

57
00:03:22,900 --> 00:03:26,900
Rym: Yeah, but if that ever really got challenged in court, I don't think it would last.

58
00:03:27,200 --> 00:03:28,084
Scott: Anyway, that's not the point.

59
00:03:28,104 --> 00:03:32,100
Scott: The point is, the trademark of the, you can't put the World of Warcraft logo.

60
00:03:32,541 --> 00:03:34,720
Scott: You gotta say World of Warcraft TM and all that business.

61
00:03:34,820 --> 00:03:39,400
Rym: Yeah, but you can do it, as long as you properly attribute it to the original trademark owner.

62
00:03:39,680 --> 00:03:39,841
Rym: Mm-hmm.

63
00:03:40,083 --> 00:03:42,900
Scott: Like, you can write a book about how McDonald's sucks, you know?

64
00:03:42,980 --> 00:03:44,205
Rym: Yeah, I mean, this guy did that.

65
00:03:44,867 --> 00:03:48,400
Rym: In my opinion, his guide is no different, and he even uses this example in his lawsuit.

66
00:03:49,100 --> 00:03:52,600
Rym: His book is no different than someone writing a book about how to use Microsoft Word.

67
00:03:53,180 --> 00:03:54,080
Scott: Yeah, basically.

68
00:03:54,580 --> 00:04:01,640
Rym: And because this is a game, and because Blizzard is evil and stupid, they've decided to crush him under the weight of their legal system and their lawyers.

69
00:04:02,301 --> 00:04:05,180
Rym: And he fought back, and he's suing them, and we'll see what comes of it.

70
00:04:05,741 --> 00:04:09,440
Scott: He's probably gonna win, because if he doesn't, well, say goodbye to a lot of the computer books.

71
00:04:09,660 --> 00:04:11,340
Rym: Say goodbye to every computer book ever written.

72
00:04:11,582 --> 00:04:12,730
Scott: Say goodbye to a lot of books.

73
00:04:12,750 --> 00:04:13,960
Scott: Say goodbye to a lot of free speech.

74
00:04:14,320 --> 00:04:14,541
Rym: Yeah.

75
00:04:15,424 --> 00:04:22,499
Rym: And for all of you out there who play World of Warcraft, a nice little dig I've got for you is that, if you're still playing, you're supporting a company who does something like this.

76
00:04:23,180 --> 00:04:31,860
Scott: Yeah, you're giving money to someone who is squelching free speech, and in exchange, they're twiddling some bits in a database whenever you click.

77
00:04:33,182 --> 00:04:33,767
Scott: That's all it is.

78
00:04:33,807 --> 00:04:35,400
Scott: You click, and a number changes.

79
00:04:35,760 --> 00:04:39,400
Scott: And you're paying them money for the privilege of clicking and letting numbers change.

80
00:04:39,762 --> 00:04:41,851
Scott: Oh, wait, you get a chat room too, but those are free.

81
00:04:42,313 --> 00:04:43,900
Scott: You can get them from IRC for nothing.

82
00:04:44,341 --> 00:04:49,259
Rym: Well, if you play IRC in one window and have Progress Quest going in the other window, and you call yourself the same thing in both of them.

83
00:04:49,740 --> 00:04:50,584
Scott: Yeah, there you go.

84
00:04:51,268 --> 00:04:53,800
Scott: I'm level 50... I'm almost level 60 in Progress Quest.

85
00:04:54,785 --> 00:04:55,773
Rym: Ah.

86
00:04:55,793 --> 00:04:56,599
Rym: What class are you again?

87
00:04:57,422 --> 00:04:58,974
Scott: I am a... I forget.

88
00:04:59,014 --> 00:04:59,800
Scott: An Ur-Paladin.

89
00:05:00,081 --> 00:05:00,336
Scott: Uh-huh.

90
00:05:00,621 --> 00:05:04,240
Scott: And I think my race is like something... Enchanted Motorcycle.

91
00:05:04,400 --> 00:05:04,529
Scott: Great.

92
00:05:05,044 --> 00:05:05,216
Scott: Yeah.

93
00:05:05,622 --> 00:05:07,040
Rym: It sounds very Kingdom Alothing.

94
00:05:07,684 --> 00:05:08,669
Scott: Yeah, it doesn't... I don't care.

95
00:05:08,890 --> 00:05:11,606
Scott: I just let it... It runs in the system tray, and I hardly ever look at it.

96
00:05:12,049 --> 00:05:13,236
Scott: I look at it like in the morning.

97
00:05:13,659 --> 00:05:13,880
Scott: Anyway.

98
00:05:14,940 --> 00:05:19,600
Scott: Whether you know it or not, Final Fantasy XII is out in Japan.

99
00:05:19,600 --> 00:05:21,723
Scott: 12.

100
00:05:21,723 --> 00:05:24,552
Scott: As in, I consider VI to be the best one.

101
00:05:24,572 --> 00:05:28,364
Scott: There have been two times that many, if you don't count X2.

102
00:05:28,505 --> 00:05:30,391
Scott: So, in fact, it's kind of like XIII.

103
00:05:30,572 --> 00:05:36,600
Scott: And XI, I guess... Well, count it as XII, because XI's an MMO, and X2 was a real game, kinda.

104
00:05:37,621 --> 00:05:41,779
Scott: Anything higher than VI, you know, kinda higher than VII is definitely sucky.

105
00:05:42,460 --> 00:05:42,804
Rym: Well, no, no.

106
00:05:42,824 --> 00:05:43,329
Rym: Just different.

107
00:05:43,350 --> 00:05:44,340
Rym: They're not the same kind of game.

108
00:05:44,740 --> 00:05:44,881
Scott: Yeah.

109
00:05:45,001 --> 00:05:45,322
Scott: Anyway.

110
00:05:45,824 --> 00:05:46,628
Scott: So, XII.

111
00:05:47,190 --> 00:05:48,656
Scott: XII is this weird thing.

112
00:05:48,696 --> 00:05:52,695
Scott: I've been reading about it, and I sent you probably the best article on the internet about it.

113
00:05:52,715 --> 00:05:54,379
Scott: Of course, it's IGN, so what do you want?

114
00:05:54,540 --> 00:06:03,295
Rym: Yeah, I've been seeing general sorts of brouhaha where people say that this betrayed the core of Final Fantasy, and other people said that it's not even a Final Fantasy game.

115
00:06:03,315 --> 00:06:08,420
Rym: But some of the really old school people said it goes back to the good roots of what it should be, and no one agrees.

116
00:06:08,620 --> 00:06:14,216
Scott: Let me tell you, from what I've read, this is my interpretation of what the words I have seen on the internet.

117
00:06:14,300 --> 00:06:15,720
Rym: Yeah, we haven't actually played the game.

118
00:06:15,840 --> 00:06:16,623
Scott: No, I have not.

119
00:06:16,704 --> 00:06:18,331
Scott: And it's in Japanese, so I don't see the point.

120
00:06:18,893 --> 00:06:22,045
Scott: Number one, it still has the crazy FMVs and the crazy plot.

121
00:06:22,266 --> 00:06:24,894
Scott: that's just as good as any other Final Fantasy game.

122
00:06:25,376 --> 00:06:25,737
Scott: Hooray.

123
00:06:26,239 --> 00:06:27,663
Scott: Nothing has changed in this department.

124
00:06:28,105 --> 00:06:30,793
Scott: So if you only play for the plot, go for you.

125
00:06:31,415 --> 00:06:37,819
Scott: Number two, it's got the item, magic, whatever system seems to have this weird new thing with, like, licenses.

126
00:06:37,900 --> 00:06:45,140
Scott: Like, if you want to use a sword, you need to get a sword license, and then get a sword, and then you give the sword license to the character, and then the character can have the sword.

127
00:06:45,560 --> 00:06:49,260
Rym: Yeah, but every Final Fantasy after seven or so has had something weird like that.

128
00:06:49,640 --> 00:06:51,313
Scott: Yeah, it's just, that's their weird thing.

129
00:06:51,353 --> 00:06:52,260
Scott: I'm just explaining what it is.

130
00:06:52,320 --> 00:06:53,340
Rym: Yeah, everyone has a weird thing.

131
00:06:53,400 --> 00:06:56,578
Scott: Now, the thing that seems to be getting the most attention is the combat system.

132
00:06:56,699 --> 00:07:03,580
Scott: Now, let me just say my opinion on, if you don't know it already, on current, average RPG combat systems.

133
00:07:03,580 --> 00:07:06,132
Rym: I think we can sum it up very succinctly.

134
00:07:06,373 --> 00:07:07,820
Rym: We don't have time for that shit anymore.

135
00:07:08,200 --> 00:07:09,767
Scott: Yeah, okay, this is what I want to do.

136
00:07:09,888 --> 00:07:23,583
Scott: As I'm walking around exploring a dungeon, the fun part of the game, I want to, every, say, ten or so steps in the dungeon, meet an encounter where I have to push A repeatedly to make a number go up and continue doing the fun part.

137
00:07:23,905 --> 00:07:24,627
Scott: Yeah, that's great.

138
00:07:24,908 --> 00:07:25,752
Scott: That's just terrific.

139
00:07:26,193 --> 00:07:28,000
Scott: That hasn't changed in forever.

140
00:07:28,440 --> 00:07:37,452
Rym: Now, I didn't mind it so much when I was young, but the combat was fun back then, and by the time I got tedious, I'd already moved on, and I had just invented free time to spend playing these games.

141
00:07:37,895 --> 00:07:41,459
Rym: No, not so much, and I just get annoyed when I have to fight more often than I wanted to.

142
00:07:41,840 --> 00:07:48,484
Scott: So, the new Final Fantasy XII combat, from what I've read and from what I've seen, works kinda like this.

143
00:07:49,026 --> 00:07:52,620
Scott: You have a bunch of characters, and you set AI on them.

144
00:07:52,740 --> 00:08:00,029
Scott: Now, the AI isn't like other AIs, where you set, like, you know, "Okay, you attack a lot, and you defend a lot, and you heal a

145
00:08:00,069 --> 00:08:00,270
Scott: lot.".

146
00:08:00,330 --> 00:08:01,456
Scott: It's not simple like that.

147
00:08:01,617 --> 00:08:19,004
Scott: It's, you set things called "gambits" on the characters, where you can say, you lay out very specific strategies, like, "You rush in and attack, and when your HP is low, run back, and, you know, you, you know, cast this spell, but when the HP is low, cast your healing

148
00:08:19,044 --> 00:08:19,607
Scott: spell.".

149
00:08:19,788 --> 00:08:24,169
Rym: Like an extremely advanced version of the Secret of Mana AI.

150
00:08:24,772 --> 00:08:26,740
Rym: Extremely advanced and specific.

151
00:08:27,080 --> 00:08:30,679
Scott: Yeah, you tell everyone exactly, pretty much almost exactly what to do.

152
00:08:31,260 --> 00:08:37,144
Scott: Then, you kinda point your characters in a direction and go, and they just constantly fight.

153
00:08:37,465 --> 00:08:43,275
Scott: Like, you just point them north, and they'll start walking north, and as you encounter bad guys, they'll go over and fight them.

154
00:08:43,316 --> 00:08:49,300
Scott: It'll look like, it looks like a bunch of people running through terrain while fighting bad guys.

155
00:08:49,480 --> 00:08:51,392
Scott: You know, it's pretty cinematic and whatnot.

156
00:08:51,654 --> 00:08:52,519
Rym: It sounds really badass.

157
00:08:53,420 --> 00:08:56,111
Scott: The problem with this is, well, let's forget the problem.

158
00:08:56,392 --> 00:09:10,980
Scott: One more thing about it is that you get this, too, this passive mode and active mode, and it's basically the old active and wait business, where in the passive mode, if you pause to change something, the fighting will stop, and in active mode, the fighting will continue if you go to the menu.

159
00:09:11,580 --> 00:09:14,700
Rym: I played every Final Fantasy that had that option in passive mode.

160
00:09:14,920 --> 00:09:18,240
Scott: I always played with wait, as opposed to active, so yeah, it's the same thing.

161
00:09:19,001 --> 00:09:24,846
Scott: Anyway, the thing people are complaining about is, is that once you set up the AI, you don't really do anything.

162
00:09:24,886 --> 00:09:28,806
Scott: You just kinda point forward and go, and your guys do everything on their own.

163
00:09:28,846 --> 00:09:29,790
Scott: You don't have to touch anything.

164
00:09:30,413 --> 00:09:39,654
Scott: Now, on the one hand, that makes me really happy, because I hate having to push A a million times to continue, and it's, you know, it gets past the annoying parts of the game.

165
00:09:40,257 --> 00:09:43,525
Scott: On the other hand, so what's the game?

166
00:09:43,565 --> 00:09:44,951
Scott: You're not doing anything.

167
00:09:45,292 --> 00:09:50,093
Rym: Well, I guess it depends on how often you have to change up the strategy or how long these sequences are.

168
00:09:50,113 --> 00:09:52,484
Rym: I mean, is it a game of walk around and talk to people?

169
00:09:52,504 --> 00:09:54,934
Rym: Is it a game of find the secrets in the dungeon?

170
00:09:54,954 --> 00:09:59,859
Rym: Is it a game of make the party that'll make it through the dangerous area and pick the right path to do it?

171
00:10:00,701 --> 00:10:05,422
Scott: We don't quite know yet, because I haven't played it, and I've only read a few sparse writings on the internet.

172
00:10:05,784 --> 00:10:07,634
Rym: Yeah, well, it's on, what, the PlayStation 2?

173
00:10:07,634 --> 00:10:07,815
Scott: Yep.

174
00:10:08,116 --> 00:10:12,840
Rym: Well, we're probably gonna get a PlayStation 2 whenever the 3 comes out, so maybe we'll pick it up when it comes out over here.

175
00:10:13,280 --> 00:10:14,870
Scott: The other thing, there are two other things.

176
00:10:14,910 --> 00:10:17,002
Scott: Number one, you don't get gold from enemies anymore.

177
00:10:17,082 --> 00:10:20,920
Scott: All you do is find gold and treasure, and then you can sell treasure to get gold.

178
00:10:21,621 --> 00:10:25,260
Scott: When you're in towns, you can't just walk around talking to people, like in the olden days.

179
00:10:25,800 --> 00:10:32,057
Scott: Some people will talk to you, and some people won't talk to you, and if someone's gonna talk to you, they'll have a little bubble above their head that says, "I will talk to

180
00:10:32,098 --> 00:10:32,178
Scott: you.".

181
00:10:33,201 --> 00:10:34,892
Scott: So you don't just walk up to random people and say,

182
00:10:34,933 --> 00:10:35,154
Scott: "Hey.".

183
00:10:35,194 --> 00:10:36,221
Scott: They'll just be like, "Who the hell are you

184
00:10:36,241 --> 00:10:36,663
Scott: going?".

185
00:10:37,125 --> 00:10:40,663
Rym: Well, it seems to me that in original old Final Fantasies, you didn't walk up to people and say,

186
00:10:40,703 --> 00:10:40,884
Rym: "Hey.".

187
00:10:41,145 --> 00:10:43,958
Rym: You walk up to people, and they would just tell you a sentence.

188
00:10:44,219 --> 00:10:44,400
Scott: Yep.

189
00:10:44,660 --> 00:10:46,813
Rym: And if you talk to them again, they would tell you the same sentence again.

190
00:10:47,276 --> 00:10:48,462
Rym: Sometimes that sentence would change.

191
00:10:48,563 --> 00:10:54,168
Scott: I think the reason they've done this is because they wanted to add people to the town who weren't, who didn't have text.

192
00:10:54,208 --> 00:10:56,738
Scott: That way they could make more highly populated areas.

193
00:10:56,859 --> 00:10:57,642
Rym: Which is a good idea.

194
00:10:57,762 --> 00:10:58,846
Scott: Yeah, that's fine.

195
00:10:59,288 --> 00:11:06,694
Scott: But yeah, it seems like on the one hand, they tried to appease people like me by making combat less tedious, which pissed off all the people.

196
00:11:07,036 --> 00:11:11,451
Scott: Literally, I think I saw a guy who said, "Man, I want to push buttons.

197
00:11:11,471 --> 00:11:13,176
Scott: I don't want my combat to just

198
00:11:13,216 --> 00:11:13,638
Scott: happen.".

199
00:11:13,778 --> 00:11:15,586
Scott: I'm like, "Okay, so you want to push A a million

200
00:11:15,626 --> 00:11:16,028
Scott: times.".

201
00:11:16,169 --> 00:11:20,870
Rym: Yeah, I was always the kind of gamer, even when I liked these games, because I freaking love Final Fantasy IV.

202
00:11:21,473 --> 00:11:23,843
Rym: Whenever I could, I would just hold down A to B to combat.

203
00:11:24,043 --> 00:11:24,244
Scott: Yep.

204
00:11:24,706 --> 00:11:29,443
Rym: I actually unequipped Rose's arrows most of the time so that I could just hold down A and not waste my arrows.

