00:23:56,383 --> 00:24:01,560
Rym: It becomes broken when you've played the game enough to where you know all the cards, and you know how they all work.

409
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:05,856
Scott: Yeah, the thing is, uh, it's sort of like this double-edged sword.

410
00:24:05,877 --> 00:24:11,686
Scott: On the one hand, the cards aren't very varied, because if, you know, if they were varied, they might be more interesting.

411
00:24:11,726 --> 00:24:13,335
Scott: Like, "Ooh, this is a different kind of card,

412
00:24:13,375 --> 00:24:13,737
Scott: hooray!".

413
00:24:14,381 --> 00:24:21,060
Scott: But at the same time, if they were all varied, then as soon as you heard the beginning of them, you'd know exactly what the card was if you had played before.

414
00:24:21,400 --> 00:24:25,105
Scott: So the fact that there are, like, ten cards that start with "Pirates,".

415
00:24:25,427 --> 00:24:29,620
Scott: you don't know which of the ten cards it is, so there's still your gambling when you make your decision.

416
00:24:30,260 --> 00:24:34,580
Rym: Now, the other interesting aspect of the game, aside from these cards, are the spaceships.

417
00:24:34,660 --> 00:24:35,740
Scott: The spaceships are awesome.

418
00:24:35,800 --> 00:24:38,780
Rym: These are probably the most enduring icon of this game.

419
00:24:39,120 --> 00:24:42,740
Rym: Every player gets a giant, well-designed plastic spaceship.

420
00:24:43,300 --> 00:24:47,280
Rym: The spaceship has places on it to stick various kinds of upgrades that you get throughout the game.

421
00:24:47,760 --> 00:24:56,860
Rym: In addition, the spaceship is filled with multi-colored balls, and when you shake the spaceship up and then put it down, two of those balls become visible, and that is how you roll.

422
00:24:57,940 --> 00:25:03,520
Scott: Yep, well, it's not how you roll the dice for resources, but it is how you roll to see how well your spaceship does every round.

423
00:25:03,920 --> 00:25:05,632
Rym: Yep, and just various tests in the game.

424
00:25:05,753 --> 00:25:06,800
Rym: It's also how cards appear.

425
00:25:07,220 --> 00:25:09,460
Scott: Yep, it's usually fighting against other players.

426
00:25:10,040 --> 00:25:12,320
Rym: Now, the basic game is just like any Settlers game.

427
00:25:12,380 --> 00:25:15,600
Rym: You start on some planets, you want to colonize more planets.

428
00:25:16,081 --> 00:25:19,560
Rym: Some planets have crap on them, you've got to get the crap off before you can put your guys there.

429
00:25:20,361 --> 00:25:28,779
Scott: I hate that, because it's like, you can get somewhere and colonize it, but it has this terrible, like, block on it, and you can't get the block off because you don't have enough other stuff.

430
00:25:29,400 --> 00:25:31,200
Rym: Yep, and of course, there's pirates about.

431
00:25:32,845 --> 00:25:33,035
Scott: Arrrrrrr.

432
00:25:33,441 --> 00:25:46,380
Rym: Now, honestly, even though the game is broken just like every other Catan game is, if you have a bunch of friends who like German board games and have never played Starfares of Catan before, it's well worth it to get them all together and play that game a few times.

433
00:25:46,800 --> 00:25:53,559
Scott: This is the kind of game where if you're at a convention or something and you see the game there, just pick, and you've never played it, pick it up and do it.

434
00:25:53,960 --> 00:25:57,960
Scott: But I wouldn't recommend you buy it, because it's kind of big and expensive.

435
00:25:58,240 --> 00:25:59,559
Rym: Yeah, convince someone else to buy it.

436
00:26:00,021 --> 00:26:01,260
Scott: Oh yeah, that's a great idea.

437
00:26:01,500 --> 00:26:01,587
Scott: Yeah.

438
00:26:02,100 --> 00:26:06,600
Scott: Because they'll play it like one or two times, and then the bottom of the spaceship seems to break.

439
00:26:06,880 --> 00:26:13,460
Scott: Like, the little things that hold the boosters on seem to break, so you'd feel really bad if it was your spaceship's breaking, but if it's someone else's, who cares?

440
00:26:14,300 --> 00:26:19,140
Rym: Now, the one thing about the game is the way it's designed, it's very hard to run away with the game.

441
00:26:19,861 --> 00:26:35,880
Scott: Yeah, like in the original Settlers, plain old Settlers, you can frickin, if you build a couple cities and some settlements before other people do, or you go at just the right time and they keep rolling your number, you can just get 10 points and everyone else can't do anything.

442
00:26:36,140 --> 00:26:43,860
Rym: Yeah, this game basically has a lot of Mario Kart kind of elastics in there that'll hold a front player's back and back player's front, just a little bit.

443
00:26:44,400 --> 00:26:50,158
Scott: Yeah, like I was doing pretty poorly, and then all of a sudden, who knows, I'm in second place, and then, uh, I didn't do so well, but...

444
00:26:50,380 --> 00:26:59,646
Rym: Yeah, and meanwhile, I was in last place for a while, but meanwhile, everyone's colonizing, I have craps, I just made a couple ships and I sent them off into the far reaches of space and forgot about them.

445
00:27:00,068 --> 00:27:01,800
Rym: Like, everyone was ignoring me because I was losing.

446
00:27:02,241 --> 00:27:13,220
Rym: And those ships eventually made it to the planets on the other side of the board, I colonized them, I got one victory point away from winning, then I sat there almost winning and failing over and over again until someone else won.

447
00:27:13,541 --> 00:27:24,544
Scott: Yeah, my problem was two of my ships during the game just, like, went to go colonize places, and then when they got there, couldn't actually colonize, or someone else, like, jumped right in front of me.

448
00:27:24,564 --> 00:27:36,740
Scott: So I ended up with these ships that were trying to do something, but for, like, I could have had, like, you know, four ships worth of stuff, but in the end I had two ships that didn't do anything because they couldn't get anywhere fast enough.

449
00:27:37,400 --> 00:27:46,420
Rym: The game also has a really cool alien science kind of thing where you can go off and talk to aliens, and you get victory points, and two, you get technology from them.

450
00:27:47,181 --> 00:27:50,420
Scott: Yeah, it's like there are these, what, four or five alien spots on the board?

451
00:27:50,560 --> 00:27:52,716
Rym: Just things like, now your boosters are faster, or, etc.

452
00:27:53,781 --> 00:27:59,120
Scott: Yeah, you go to them and you trade goods with them, and I think there are five spots for each alien, and there are five cards.

453
00:27:59,481 --> 00:28:04,900
Rym: Yeah, and whoever has, you can control the aliens, whoever controls the aliens gets two extra victory points, kind of like longest road.

454
00:28:05,100 --> 00:28:15,449
Scott: Yeah, and each alien has a different kind of bonus, like, one of them has, like, bonuses to your ship, and one of them has bonuses to your resources, and one of them has, like, the cheating bonus.

455
00:28:15,610 --> 00:28:17,020
Scott: that kind of unbalances the game.

456
00:28:17,360 --> 00:28:17,472
Rym: Yep.

457
00:28:17,960 --> 00:28:18,050
Scott: Yeah.

458
00:28:18,500 --> 00:28:22,260
Scott: So you just, you know, you try to trade with those aliens to get stuff, and whatever.

459
00:28:22,680 --> 00:28:23,600
Rym: But it was a fun game.

460
00:28:24,020 --> 00:28:30,040
Rym: If anything, it's in the old style of German board game, in that high production values, lots of little bits.

461
00:28:30,760 --> 00:28:35,720
Scott: Yeah, it's more the family type of game than the hardcore type of game, I would say.

462
00:28:36,363 --> 00:28:44,139
Rym: Once again, like Scott said, it's a great game to get people into games like this at a con, or to get the creepy old guy with a lot of money to buy and then play it with him.

463
00:28:44,800 --> 00:28:52,020
Scott: Oh yeah, this, if you got a family too, they'll love this, because they'll just love, anyone will love playing with the spaceships, no matter how hard the game itself actually is.

464
00:28:52,220 --> 00:28:58,180
Rym: And of course, it's a thousand times more intellectually stimulating than Monopoly or Life.

465
00:28:58,560 --> 00:28:59,760
Scott: Yeah, Life.

466
00:29:00,402 --> 00:29:03,400
Scott: I heard the greatest quote about the game of Life on this board game podcast.

467
00:29:03,541 --> 00:29:06,597
Scott: He said, "The worst game in the world with the best spinner in the

468
00:29:06,617 --> 00:29:06,919
Scott: world.".

469
00:29:07,981 --> 00:29:12,120
Rym: Actually, my parents, when I was young, we used to play Life like once a month, like a thing.

470
00:29:12,821 --> 00:29:17,939
Rym: And all I remember is that I learned how to get exactly whatever number I wanted, no matter what with that spinner.

471
00:29:18,160 --> 00:29:19,120
Scott: Best spinner in the world.

472
00:29:19,742 --> 00:29:21,039
Rym: Yeah, they were none too pleased with that.

473
00:29:21,380 --> 00:29:25,100
Scott: We had to put graphite on our spinner to get it all lubricated and such.

474
00:29:26,709 --> 00:29:27,399
Scott: It was a nice trick.

475
00:29:28,060 --> 00:29:32,180
Scott: That thing was, they would literally fly, like, zzzzzzzzzzzzzz.

476
00:29:32,240 --> 00:29:32,659
Scott: It was great.

477
00:29:33,440 --> 00:29:36,320
Scott: Anyway, so, Galactic Civilizations 2.

478
00:29:36,320 --> 00:29:38,140
Scott: Well, I could talk a long time about this game.

479
00:29:38,520 --> 00:29:39,438
Rym: Yeah, I didn't actually play it.

480
00:29:39,740 --> 00:29:46,059
Scott: All right, so, if you've ever played a Master of Orion space conquest game, this is another one of those.

481
00:29:46,780 --> 00:29:46,886
Rym: Great.

482
00:29:48,581 --> 00:29:52,580
Scott: Um, it does a few things better than previous versions.

483
00:29:52,760 --> 00:29:55,859
Scott: Obviously, there's some updated graphics, et cetera, et cetera.

484
00:29:56,542 --> 00:30:01,820
Scott: New Alien Race is fancy looking spaceships, blah blah blah blah blah.

485
00:30:01,960 --> 00:30:02,556
Scott: All that good stuff.

486
00:30:04,260 --> 00:30:10,480
Scott: Is there a reason to play this instead of Master of Orion 2, besides the fact that it works more easily on modern computers?

487
00:30:11,567 --> 00:30:11,998
Scott: Yes and no.

488
00:30:13,000 --> 00:30:17,140
Scott: The first problem I had with this game was that I couldn't really figure out how it worked.

489
00:30:17,340 --> 00:30:18,719
Scott: Maybe that's because I don't have the manual.

490
00:30:19,140 --> 00:30:20,619
Scott: That, I think, had a lot to do with it.

491
00:30:20,940 --> 00:30:23,134
Rym: I wonder why you don't have the manual, Mr.

492
00:30:23,234 --> 00:30:24,100
Rym: Pirate McPirate?

493
00:30:25,362 --> 00:30:28,020
Scott: Uh, there was that story, they wanted everyone to pirate it.

494
00:30:28,060 --> 00:30:29,797
Scott: And I pirated it before- No, no, no, no.

495
00:30:30,262 --> 00:30:33,139
Scott: That was before I saw the story that said, "No, we actually

496
00:30:33,179 --> 00:30:33,320
Scott: don't.".

497
00:30:34,221 --> 00:30:38,440
Rym: Um, I think it was obvious because the people who wanted you to pirate were, in fact, Star Force.

498
00:30:38,742 --> 00:30:39,340
Scott: Oh, it doesn't matter.

499
00:30:40,266 --> 00:30:41,960
Rym: The hated evil of all the internet.

500
00:30:42,240 --> 00:30:43,920
Scott: Well, it doesn't matter because I deleted it now.

501
00:30:44,181 --> 00:30:45,480
Scott: I don't need to play this game anymore.

502
00:30:47,644 --> 00:30:48,840
Rym: So they still didn't get any money.

503
00:30:49,506 --> 00:30:49,718
Scott: No.

504
00:30:50,280 --> 00:30:55,140
Scott: Which probably is fine if the game uses- So it didn't really matter.

505
00:30:55,501 --> 00:31:00,079
Rym: Yeah, if the game's as mediocre as you seem to say it was, then- Well, it's not that it's mediocre.

506
00:31:00,400 --> 00:31:04,700
Scott: It's a really good space conquest game, if you really like space conquest games.

507
00:31:04,800 --> 00:31:09,280
Scott: The problem, I think, is in me that I can't deal with the tedium of micromanagement anymore.

508
00:31:09,880 --> 00:31:13,580
Rym: Yeah, I mean, I've had this problem, like I've mentioned, I've been playing Civ 2 a lot lately.

509
00:31:13,742 --> 00:31:14,859
Rym: Just because I love that old game.

510
00:31:15,980 --> 00:31:20,640
Rym: And I can't, like, it's actually painful to play on anything other than the smallest map.

511
00:31:21,161 --> 00:31:23,380
Rym: Because with the small map, you know, I expand.

512
00:31:23,906 --> 00:31:25,020
Rym: And then everyone expands.

513
00:31:25,200 --> 00:31:27,260
Rym: And then there's just a game of, you know, manage my little civilization.

514
00:31:27,960 --> 00:31:31,180
Rym: On the large maps, it's the game of, there's a giant island over there.

515
00:31:31,641 --> 00:31:32,919
Rym: And no one knows it's there but me.

516
00:31:33,420 --> 00:31:40,360
Rym: All I'd have to do is put settlers on it and send it over there and colonize the whole island and- But in order to do that, you have to push so many buttons.

517
00:31:40,941 --> 00:31:43,820
Rym: It's just like, fuck it, I'll let the Aztecs have that island, whatever.

518
00:31:44,864 --> 00:31:45,699
Rym: It's not worth it to me.

519
00:31:45,960 --> 00:31:49,360
Scott: I don't want to push all the buttons necessary in order to get that island.

520
00:31:49,663 --> 00:31:50,280
Rym: Yep, yep.

521
00:31:50,482 --> 00:31:51,199
Scott: Even though I could.

522
00:31:51,300 --> 00:31:55,360
Scott: It's like, I could win, I just don't want to push the button to make me win.

523
00:31:55,640 --> 00:31:57,219
Scott: Because I'd have to push it so many times.

524
00:31:58,120 --> 00:32:01,120
Rym: But yet you don't want the game to just have a win button because then it's not fun.

525
00:32:01,580 --> 00:32:01,673
Scott: Yep.

526
00:32:02,180 --> 00:32:08,700
Scott: So, like every other civilization type game, basically what you're doing when you play is you're controlling a bunch of sliders.

527
00:32:09,520 --> 00:32:17,600
Scott: And there's like sliders for each planet, sliders for the whole civilization, sliders for spaceships, and they all affect each other.

528
00:32:17,661 --> 00:32:19,339
Scott: But it's kind of hard to tell how.

529
00:32:19,802 --> 00:32:23,320
Scott: Like sometimes it's obvious, like, oh, if I do this, then that will happen.

530
00:32:23,420 --> 00:32:30,040
Scott: But sometimes it's like, alright, how does this affect the big picture from down here on this little old planet?

531
00:32:30,420 --> 00:32:34,120
Rym: Is there anything in it like the civilopedia that tells you exactly what everything does?

532
00:32:34,601 --> 00:32:37,980
Scott: Oh, there's text on every single thing in the game to tell you what it does.

533
00:32:38,080 --> 00:32:38,736
Rym: Did you read it?

534
00:32:39,200 --> 00:32:39,286
Rym: Yep.

535
00:32:40,320 --> 00:32:47,720
Scott: But sometimes it's not, uh, like you can tell, okay, this will increase my manufacturing by two.

536
00:32:48,522 --> 00:32:49,572
Scott: How much is two, you know?

537
00:32:50,520 --> 00:32:53,160
Scott: It's like, um, will that build it this much faster?

538
00:32:53,840 --> 00:32:56,460
Scott: Will it, would it be faster to just build something before the factory?

539
00:32:57,061 --> 00:32:58,760
Scott: And you have to end up doing all this annoying math.

540
00:32:59,520 --> 00:33:01,860
Scott: And you get like all these different numbers all over the place.

541
00:33:02,441 --> 00:33:13,430
Scott: And it's like they made it lighter than something like Master of Orion 2 or 3, which is pretty heavy, but they didn't make it light enough as to where it's like.

542
00:33:13,531 --> 00:33:15,160
Scott: really just an abstract game.

543
00:33:16,222 --> 00:33:19,600
Scott: The other problem I have is there are three winning conditions.

544
00:33:19,780 --> 00:33:23,420
Scott: There's the research winning condition, the military, and the cultural one.

545
00:33:23,941 --> 00:33:28,900
Scott: The cultural one is the one I like to go for, because all you really have to do is build a lot of stuff.

546
00:33:30,420 --> 00:33:37,980
Scott: You know, you just build like, uh, all these entertainment facilities, and then your borders just slowly expand without you having to do anything.

547
00:33:38,461 --> 00:33:42,860
Scott: All you do is have planets and build stuff on them and keep building stuff.

548
00:33:43,001 --> 00:33:46,980
Scott: And eventually you'll just conquer the galaxy without doing anything, except building.

549
00:33:48,321 --> 00:33:51,560
Scott: If you want to do the research one, well it's pretty similar.

550
00:33:51,720 --> 00:33:58,499
Scott: You just have to go around and micromanage all your planets to maximize research, and then just keep researching until you win.

551
00:33:58,961 --> 00:34:01,119
Scott: And you want to trade a lot of research if you do that also.

552
00:34:01,900 --> 00:34:05,764
Scott: The military one, see this is the one that's always a problem, is the.

553
00:34:05,926 --> 00:34:09,500
Scott: the fun way to play is military, because you fly spaceships at each other and they shoot.

554
00:34:10,224 --> 00:34:12,620
Scott: I actually didn't experience combat once.

555
00:34:13,420 --> 00:34:13,755
Scott: Not once.

556
00:34:14,320 --> 00:34:14,385
Rym: Wow.

557
00:34:15,621 --> 00:34:20,659
Rym: No matter how peaceful a game I ever try to play in Civ 2, it always ends up with like, the Zulus coming in with tanks.

558
00:34:20,900 --> 00:34:27,679
Scott: Well you see, I always researched the technologies that added to my diplomacy, and I gave myself a diplomacy bonus when I customized my race.

559
00:34:28,239 --> 00:34:30,820
Scott: So because I'm playing against the computer, they'll do whatever I say.

560
00:34:31,322 --> 00:34:31,591
Rym: Uh-huh.

561
00:34:32,101 --> 00:34:39,659
Scott: I can see this being a problem in multiplayer, because diplomacy points don't mean shit, and there's so many buildings- You know what happened?

562
00:34:39,980 --> 00:34:40,976
Rym: Rym's tanks would come in.

563
00:34:41,520 --> 00:34:57,620
Scott: There's so many buildings that just, and stuff in the game that gives you diplomacy points, that, you know, it's such a key part of the strategy, that the multiplayer I think would just break it, unless they like, maybe you could use diplomacy points to force other people's hands.

564
00:34:57,920 --> 00:35:02,860
Rym: Well I mean, I just use Civ 2 because I consider it one of the best games of this type ever.

565
00:35:04,060 --> 00:35:07,019
Rym: And because I haven't played Civ 4, which people have said is better, but I don't know.

566
00:35:07,443 --> 00:35:17,400
Rym: But in that game, even in the multiplayer, like say you have the Great Wall, or some sort of high diplomacy, the game would actually force other people to offer peace, or a ceasefire, or things like that.

567
00:35:17,460 --> 00:35:18,359
Rym: It would force their hand.

568
00:35:19,040 --> 00:35:21,120
Scott: Yeah, but Shoukei, a guy agrees to peace.

569
00:35:21,260 --> 00:35:22,859
Scott: He can still break the peace and shoot you.

570
00:35:23,280 --> 00:35:27,699
Rym: Yeah, unless the game decides to not let him do that for X turns, or has penalties for doing so.

571
00:35:28,286 --> 00:35:28,371
Scott: Yeah.

572
00:35:28,820 --> 00:35:32,080
Rym: Maybe your government gets overthrown, maybe some aliens appear and kill you, I don't know.

573
00:35:32,200 --> 00:35:46,440
Scott: That is one thing I really liked in this game, is once you get past the initial stages, you get to Republic and Democratic type of governments, and what'll happen is every turn is a week, right, in game time.

574
00:35:47,501 --> 00:36:13,300
Scott: Every so often, there'll be an election, and you'll actually see, you know, if you don't have enough influence, which is one of the sliders that you can't control directly, you just build things to increase influence, if you don't have enough influence over your people, then you'll get voted out of your government, and you can see they'll actually do an election with a picture of a parliament or whatever, and the voting, and what percent of the voting you got.

575
00:36:13,341 --> 00:36:14,539
Rym: What happens if you get voted out?

576
00:36:14,660 --> 00:36:16,860
Rym: Do you just overthrow the government and come back, or what?

577
00:36:17,660 --> 00:36:23,239
Scott: Actually, what I think happens is if you are voted favorably, you get a bonus.

578
00:36:23,620 --> 00:36:25,520
Scott: Like, I was always voted favorably.

579
00:36:25,600 --> 00:36:30,500
Scott: I had the majority party, like, all the time, so I got a plus 20 to my economic bonus.

580
00:36:31,103 --> 00:36:34,501
Scott: If I would have been voted down, I would have had, like, a minus 20.

581
00:36:34,501 --> 00:36:39,820
Rym: Wait, so all we'd have to do if we lived in that world is always vote for whoever's in office, and then the economy's just booming?

582
00:36:40,681 --> 00:36:52,040
Scott: Yes, but the problem is that, from a game perspective, it's if you want to be a democracy, you have the chance to get a bonus if you keep your influence up.

583
00:36:52,581 --> 00:36:57,380
Scott: If you don't pick democracy, you can forget influence, but other people might be getting a bonus.

584
00:36:58,080 --> 00:37:02,360
Scott: But on the other hand, if you choose democracy and don't keep the influence up, you're gonna get a minus.

585
00:37:02,920 --> 00:37:02,989
Rym: Huh.

586
00:37:03,900 --> 00:37:09,979
Scott: There are other cool things that happen, like, a lot of games have random events, like, this happened, you know, what do you do?

587
00:37:10,440 --> 00:37:14,100
Scott: Or it's like, this happened, your people die.

588
00:37:14,742 --> 00:37:17,499
Scott: In this game, it's this happened, and it gives you three choices.

589
00:37:17,720 --> 00:37:24,200
Scott: The three choices are usually, like, evil, good, and yin yang, you know, and they'll have different effects.

590
00:37:24,320 --> 00:37:26,619
Scott: Like, your people are protesting, what do you do?

591
00:37:27,181 --> 00:37:27,658
Scott: Shoot them.

592
00:37:27,920 --> 00:37:32,200
Scott: Yeah, it's like, freedom of speech, well, then you're gonna have, you know, this effect.

593
00:37:33,060 --> 00:37:34,438
Scott: Uh, yin yang, no effect.

